<H1><FONT color=3D#000fff>Synthesis of Potassium=20
tris(oxalato)ferrate</FONT></H1><FONT size=3D3><I>
<P align=3Djustify>1 lab period; work in pairs. Complete the Preparation =
page=20
before laboratory.</P></I><B><U><FONT face=3DArial size=3D3>
<P align=3Djustify>Goals</P></B></U></FONT><FONT size=3D3>
<UL>
  <LI>To improve your skill in observation=20
  <LI>To synthesize a chemical substance and purify it by =
recrystallization=20
  <LI>To discover the effect of light on the substance =
</LI></UL><B><U><FONT=20
face=3DArial size=3D3>
<P align=3Djustify>Background</P></B></U></FONT>
<P><I>Chemical synthesis</I>--the art and practice of the design and =
creation of=20
molecules--is the essence of chemistry. In no other field of science =
does the=20
practitioner have the ability to create the objects of his/her interest. =
It is=20
this single fact that sets chemistry apart from physics, geology, and =
biology,=20
in which the scientist is restricted to examining what s/he finds, =
rather than=20
what s/he creates. Chemistry has an extra dimension that combines vision =
and art=20
in the process of creating new substances with potentially new and =
exciting=20
uses.</P>
<P>This experiment provides you with an opportunity to experience =
chemical=20
synthesis first hand, and to spectroscopically characterize the molecule =
(i.e.,=20
to discover what types and energies of light the molecule interacts =
with). The=20
reaction that you will carry out is shown in equation (1).</P>
<DIR>(1): Fe<SUP>3+</SUP> + 3 C<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>4</SUB><SUP>2-</SUP> =
---&gt;=20
Fe(C<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>4</SUB>)<SUB>3</SUB><SUP>3-</SUP> </DIR>
<P>The reaction will be carried out in water solvent. This reaction is =
yet=20
another example of a class of reaction that permeates chemistry: the =
donation of=20
an electron pair by a Lewis base to a Lewis acid to form an adduct in =
which acid=20
and base are joined by a covalent bond. As we have seen and will =
continue to=20
see, the donation/acceptance of electron pairs is involved in a huge =
number of=20
chemical reactions ranging from simple laboratory processes to the =
complex=20
reactions in biological systems.</P>
<P>The adduct of Fe<SUP>3+</SUP> with oxalate ion is called a =
<I>transition=20
metal complex</I> to indicate that it is a complex molecule involving an =

electron pair donor and a transition metal ion =
(Fe<SUP>3+</SUP>).</P><U><B><FONT=20
face=3DArial size=3D3>
<P>Focus Questions</P></B></U></FONT>
<OL>
  <LI>In what molar ratio are the two reactants, iron chloride =
hexahydrate and=20
  oxalic acid, initially mixed?=20
  <LI>Propose a 3-dimensional structure for the adduct, keeping in mind =
that the=20
  oxalate ions tend to arrange themselves symmetrically around the =
iron(III)=20
  ion.=20
  <LI>In narrative form, discuss the infrared spectrum of the adduct. =
Attempt to=20
  assign observed bands to particular structural features of the adduct. =

</LI></OL><B><U><FONT face=3DArial size=3D3>
<P align=3Djustify>Equipment and Materials</P></B></U></FONT>
<UL>
  <LI>5.75" Pasteur pipets, 6 per group=20
  <LI>1 Pasteur pipet bulb=20
  <LI>Kimwipes=20
  <LI>aspirator with trap=20
  <LI>3 25-mL Erlenmeyer flasks=20
  <LI>Rubber stoppers for Erlenmeyer flasks=20
  <LI>ramrod=20
  <LI>100-mL beaker=20
  <LI>Bunsen burner=20
  <LI>Ring stand/ring/wire gauze=20
  <LI>plastic wash bottle containing distilled water=20
  <LI>Buchner funnel=20
  <LI>suction flask=20
  <LI>filter paper=20
  <LI>glass stirring rod=20
  <LI>FeCl<SUB>3</SUB>.6H<SUB>2</SUB>O=20
  <LI>oxalic acid, H<SUB>2</SUB>C<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>4</SUB>=20
  <LI>potassium hydroxide, KOH </LI></UL><B><U><FONT face=3DArial =
size=3D3>
<P align=3Djustify>Safety</P></B></U></FONT>
<P>Safety goggles must be worn at all times in the laboratory. Be very =
careful=20
around open burner flames.</P><B><U><FONT face=3DArial size=3D3>
<P align=3Djustify>Experimental</P></B></U></FONT>
<P align=3Djustify>Record your observations in your notebook.</P>
<P><B>Synthesis</B>. Obtain the required equipment. If necessary, wash =
the=20
glassware using brushes and Alconox detergent, then thoroughly rinse =
with water=20
to remove all traces of Alconox.</P>
<P>Place 6.5 millimoles (mmole) of oxalic acid,=20
H<SUB>2</SUB>C<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>4</SUB>, and 12 mmole potassium =
hydroxide in a=20
25-mL Erlenmeyer flask, and add 5 mL of distilled water. Gently heat the =
mixture=20
until the solids dissolve. To the hot solution, add 2 mmole of=20
FeCl<SUB>3</SUB>.6H<SUB>2</SUB>O and swirl to dissolve. What do you =
observe?=20
Filter the hot solution through a Kimwipe-plugged Pasteur pipet into a =
25-mL=20
Erlenmeyer flask. Stopper the flask, label it, and place it in an ice =
bath in=20
the dark for 30 minutes. During this time, the product should =
crystallize. If no=20
crystals are evident, scratch the inside wall of the Erlenmeyer with a =
glass=20
stirring rod and return the solution to the ice bath. When =
crystallization is=20
complete, collect the product by suction filtration. DO NOT WASH THE =
SOLID WITH=20
WATER. Suction the product dry.</P>
<P><B>Purification</B>. Place the product in a clean 25 Erlenmeyer. Add =
3 mL of=20
water and heat the mixture until the solid is dissolved. Once again =
place the=20
hot solution in the ice bath in the dark until the product crystallizes. =
Quickly=20
suction filter the mixture to isolate the product. Wash once with 1 mL =
of ice=20
cold water, and suction dry. Vial the solid.</P>
<P><B>Characterization</B>. If desired, you may characterize your =
product using=20
infrared and uv-visible spectroscopies. See your instructor for =
assistance.</P>
<P><B>Light Response</B>.=20
<P><B>Clean-up</B>. When you have finished all of your work,=20
<UL>
  <LI>Clean all glassware with Alconox and water, shake dry.=20
  <LI>Rinse Pasteur pipets and graduated pipets with distilled water by=20
  inserting the nozzle of your wash bottle in the top end and squirting =
water=20
  through. Aspirate dry.=20
  <LI>Return all components to the labkit.=20
  <LI>Return all borrowed equipment to the instructor before leaving =
lab.=20
</LI></UL><B><U><FONT face=3DArial size=3D3>
<P align=3Djustify>Disposal Methods</P></B></U></FONT>
<P>When finished with the experiment, hand in the vial containing your =
potassium=20
tris(oxalato)ferrate to the instructor before leaving lab. </P>
